<worksheet xml:id="notes-section-1_2">
  <title>Section 1.2 Notes</title>
    <p>
      A <alert>recurrence relation</alert> is a rule that defines a sequence by giving one or more terms at the beginning of the sequence and then defining later terms in the sequence in terms of earlier terms of the sequence.
    </p>
  

  
    <p>
      Examples:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p workspace="1in">
            Geometric sequences:
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p workspace="1in">
            Arithmetic sequences:
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p workspace="1in">
            <m>a_{0}=1,a_{n}=a_{n-1}+n</m> for <m>n \geq 1</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p workspace="1in">
            <m>a_{0}=0,a_{n}=a_{n-1}+n</m> for <m>n \geq 1</m>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p workspace="1in">
            Fibonacci sequence: <m>f_{0}=0,f_{1}=1,f_{n}=f_{n-2}+f_{n-1}</m> for <m>n \geq 2</m>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  

</worksheet>